ce:section.ce:para:
In this study, a self-synergy-powered Ni/Fe nanocube-based cholesterol assay with dual modes was developed. The multienzymic MHCF nanocube composed of nickel ion and ferricyanide ion (nickel ferrocyanide nanocube, Ni/FeNC) was prepared as versatile peroxidase (POD) mimic and catalase (CAT) mimic via a facile and cost-effective co-precipitation method. Then free radical scavengers and electron spin-trapping reagents were used to analyze the radical decomposition of H2O2 catalyzed by Ni/FeNC. Thereby, a multimode biosensor platform based on cholesterol oxidase (ChOx) and Ni/FeNC tandem catalysis was developed for sensitive and reliable detection of cholesterol (Scheme 1
                     ), where ChOx could catalyze cholesterol oxidation and offer key benefit to analytical specificity. Utilizing the H2O2 produced via the ChOx catalytic oxidation of cholesterol, OH•/O2
                     •- radicals and O2 were formed efficiently via the tandem catalysis, facilitating the generation of chemiluminescent and fluorescent signals. For CL assay, an aqueous Ni/FeNC-luminol-H2O2 CL system was fabricated, where both ferricyanide ions in Ni/FeNCs and POD-mimic-mediated radical decomposition of H2O2 could induce CL reaction via respective mechanism. Notably, both radicals-induced and ferricyanide ion-induced CL process could be enhanced by O2 in-situ generated via the CAT-like activity of Ni/FeNCs. This dual-catalyzed luminol CL system involving self-cascade catalysis of ferricyanogen and CAT mimic as well as self-synergy between POD-like and CAT-like activity of Ni/FeNCs was able to boost the intensity of CL signal efficiently. To generate fluorescent signal, OPD was introduced and oxidized to DAP by H2O2-originated radicals and O2 which were formed via CAT-like and POD-like catalysis, respectively. Then, DAP could quench the fluorescence of WS2 quantum dots via inner filter effect (IFE) for quantifying cholesterol.
